            <biogHist>
                <p>Alexander MacKenzie was born c. 1799 in Gairloch, Ross-shire and at some point
                    before 1851 moved to Uisgebhagh, Benbecula where he worked as a farmer. He had
                    at least 6 children but does not appear to have a wife still living in the 1851
                    census. His mother Mary Mackenzie was the muse of the bard William Ross and at
                    the time of the 1851 census she was living next door to her son Alexander in
                    Uisgebhagh with her daughter-in-law (another Mary, described as a 'ship owner')
                    and family, while the husband (Alexander's brother) appears to have been away at
                    sea. He was visited by Alexander Carmichael around 1866 and among other stories,
                    told him that a poem written by William Ross was written by Ross about Alexander
                    MacKenzie's mother Mary. </p>
